As an ESL contributor, I want to be able to consume esl-utils in the functional style to have a well tree-shakable code.

It is proposed to refactor `esl-utils/environment/device-detector` to the functional style.
**Important note**: object-oriented utility still should be available, we should not make breaking changes for now

*Example*:
Before:
```
@ExportNs('DeviceDetector')
export abstract class DeviceDetector {
  public static readonly isTrident = /trident/i.test(userAgent);
  public static readonly isIE = DeviceDetector.isTrident;
}
```

After: 
```
export const isTrident = /trident/i.test(userAgent);
export const isIE = isTrident;

@ExportNs('DeviceDetector')
export abstract class DeviceDetector {
  public static readonly isTrident = isTrident ;
  public static readonly isIE = isTrident;
}
```

Usage migration is out of scope for the current story, which means nothing should be changed except the current `esl-utils/environment/device-detector.ts` export, with the current DeviceDetector object available.

`Context` has several functions which are generic over `Into<T>` and such, so that the user doesn't have to call `into()` themselves, and we can do it for them. This is great, but depending on how it's done, it can harm compile times, and needlessly increase binary size.

There's a way to avoid these downsides and keep the nice API, which is to separate
the public API (with nice auto-conversions and such) from the implementation.

It would be nice to convert these the methods in Context to follow this pattern.

---

For example, `new_context` is defined as so:

```rs
    pub async fn new_context<S: Into<Address>>(&self, addr: S) -> Result<Context> {
        let addr = addr.into();
        // actual work here...
    }
```

would be transformed this version this one:

```rs
    pub async fn new_context<S: Into<Address>>(&self, addr: S) -> Result<Context> {
        self.new_context_impl(addr.into()).await
    }
    async fn new_context_impl(&self, addr: Address) -> Result<()> {
        // actual work here...
    }
```
